# Claude Code Insights

707 sessions total · 22 analyzed · 254 messages · 16h · 3 commits
2026-02-20 to 2026-02-28

## At a Glance

**What's working:** You've built a genuinely inventive multi-agent system with mayor, deacon, and witness roles running patrol loops, heartbeat checks, and escalation protocols — that's a serious architectural achievement on top of Claude Code. You also have a great instinct for ruthless simplification, like cutting a 300-line bootstrap to a minimal flow and collapsing 68 generated files into 3 clean ones. When you push back on Claude's wrong approaches, the end results are significantly better. See _Impressive Things You Did_.

**What's hindering you:** On Claude's side, it repeatedly jumps to wrong architectural assumptions (plaintext secrets, wrong tool choices, assuming commands work from any directory) instead of asking you first, and it often spirals into exploratory tool-running when it should just reason from what it already knows. On your side, the Dolt/beads infrastructure is fragile enough that the same class of corruption or initialization failure has eaten entire sessions at least six times — without a pre-flight health check, Claude ends up doing repair work instead of the actual patrol task you asked for. See _Where Things Go Wrong_.

